<br>
His bosses are those 35 million people. It's pretty simple really... if your boss(es) believe you're doing a terrible job.. you get fired. I dont see why that shouldn't be true for a political leader just the same as everyone else. I live in California but am not an American citizen. Where I'm from a Vote of No Confidence (same thing basically) is a regular part of the checks and balances of making sure our political leaders are doing an acceptable job. I find it pretty strange Americans have such a hard time dealing with the concept.<br>
<br>
Political terms are very long once elected, there needs to be some sort of checks in place that the leaders actually accomplish what they promised as their agendas rather than just wait several years until a new election. Take President Bush for instance. He campaigned as a centrist republican out to heal the partisan fighting people were sick of during the Clinton terms. Took all of about a month in office before it was very clear he was not a centrist but actually further to the right than any President in recent history. Specific campaign promises were in many cases completely reversed by him (as an example: benefits for retired military personel)... specific issues that for many people might've been a selling point to cast their vote on Bush. In Bush's case its a moot point because for better or worse (probably worse heh) he has a high approval rating. But if he had promised one thing, gotten into office and completely reversed his opinion to the point the majority of people who put him into office no longer felt him capable, a vote of no confidence would make sense no?<br>
<br>
As for this recall costing too much, one way to avoid that would be vote smarter and not elect a leader who sucks.<br>
